604. Feb. 26, 9 Edw. (1280-1). Caversham. The king to the archbishop. After thanking him for conferring a pension of ten marks a year on his clerk, Robert de Lavannia, “racione nove creacionis vestre,” until he should be otherwise provided for by the archbishop, he now requires him to confer the same on Master Walter de Brettone,5 “quia karissime amice nostre, domine regine Francia, et nobis laudabiliter est obsecutus, quem, ob ejus mores et merita, specialiter habemus recommendatum, et cujus promocionem pleno corde affectamus.”
